Operation cost is the main concern in electrocoagulation process and the maximum amount of removal at the lowest amount of cost should be achieved. The amount of electrical energy consumed (kWh) (kg COD)−1 and (kWh) (kg TOC)−1 during the removal of 1 kg of COD and TOC from biodiesel wastewater by EC at a constant applied current was calculated as a function of time according to the following equation:EEC=∫UIdt(Co,CODorTOC-Ct,CODorTOC).V.3.6=I∫Udt(Co,CODorTOC-Ct,CODorTOC)V.3.6\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{EEC}} = \frac{{\int {UI\;{\text{d}}t} }}{{(C_{\text{o,CODorTOC}} - C_{\text{t,CODorTOC}} ).V.3.6}} = \frac{{I\int {U\;{\text{d}}t} }}{{(C_{\text{o,CODorTOC}} - C_{\text{t,CODorTOC}} )\;V.3.6}}$$\end{document}where U, is the applied voltage (V), I is the current (A), t is the electrolysis time (min), Co,COD or TOC (mg/L) is the initial concentrations of COD and TOC, Ct,COD or TOC (mg/L) is the COD and TOC concentrations at time t and V (L) is the volume of treated wastewater.
